  "text": "Part 2 is devoted to the study of surfaces with p g = q = 1, K 2 = g = 3 and a pencil |G| of curves of genus 2. Xiao constructs them in [CITATION_1] by using Jacobian fibrations and modular curves, and he proves that their moduli space M 2 is 1−dimensional and it is isomorphic to the coarse moduli space of elliptic curves. Therefore one wonders whether it is possible to characterize M 2 as a subvariety of the moduli space M described by Catanese and Ciliberto. This is equivalent to characterize the elements in |D 0 | with at worst R.D.P. as singularities and containing a genus 2 pencil. Our solution is (cf. Theorem 7.1) Theorem B. There is exactly one divisor X ∈ |D 0 | containing a genus 2 pencil, and it is smooth. Moreover, let ξ i be any 2−torsion point of E different from zero, and consider the curve:",
